#Set up query as'federer or nadal or djokovic or tsitsipas' and extract tweets if they are in English
query='(federer OR nadal OR djokovic OR tsitsipas) until:2021-06-15 since:2021-05-31'
tweets=[]
limit=1000
for tweet in sntwitter.TwitterSearchScraper(query).get_items():
    if len(tweets)==limit:
        break
    else:
        if tweet.lang=='en':
            tweets.append([tweet.user.username,tweet.user.followersCount,tweet.user.statusesCount,tweet.retweetCount,tweet.rawContent,tweet.date,tweet.user.location,tweet.hashtags])
df=pd.DataFrame(tweets,columns=['User','Followers','Tweets','Retweets','Tweet text','Date','Location','Hashtags'])
df['User'] = "@" + df['User'].astype(str)
df.head()

#This function removes any URL,"@","#" and any non alphanumeric characters
def data_processing(text):
    text = text.lower()
    text = re.sub(r"https\S+|www\S+https\S+", '',text, flags=re.MULTILINE)
    text = re.sub(r'\@w+|\#','',text)
    text = re.sub(r'[^\w\s]','',text)
    return text
In [10]:
#Apply the function to our dataframe
df['Tweet text']=df['Tweet text'].apply(data_processing)

# This function calculates the polarity score of the input text using TextBlob's sentiment analysis module
def polarity(text):
    return TextBlob(text).sentiment.polarity
In [16]:
# Apply the function in the dataframe's column "Tweet text"
df['Polarity'] = df['Tweet text'].apply(polarity)
In [17]:
# This function takes a numerical sentiment polarity score as input and returns a categorical sentiment label
def sentiment(label):
    if label <0:
        return "Negative"
    elif label ==0:
        return "Neutral"
    elif label>0:
        return "Positive"
In [18]:
#Create a new column "Sentiment" with the function's sentiment label
df['Sentiment'] = df['Polarity'].apply(sentiment)
In [19]:
#This function extract the word we are looking for (rogerer,djokovic,nadal,tsitsipas) from the tweet text
def extract_word(row):
    names = []
    if 'federer' in row['Tweet text']:
        names.append('federer')
    if 'nadal' in row['Tweet text']:
        names.append('nadal')
    if 'djokovic' in row['Tweet text']:
        names.append('djokovic')
    if 'tsitsipas' in row['Tweet text']:
        names.append('tsitsipas')
    return names
In [20]:
#Create a new column "Extracted_word" with the extracted word from our function
df['Extracted_word']=df.apply(extract_word,axis=1)

tags = df['Sentiment'].value_counts()

tags.plot(kind='pie', autopct='%1.1f%%', shadow=True, colors = colors,
         startangle=90, wedgeprops = wp, explode = explode, label='')
